ce:section.ce:para:
Carbon dots (CDs), a category of zero-dimensional carbon nanomaterials renowned for their remarkable fluorescence properties, have attracted extensive attention across various fields, including environment [23,24], energy [25,26], analytical chemistry [27,28], and catalysis [29,30]. Importantly, CDs exhibit lower toxicity, environmentally friendly synthetic procedures, stable fluorescence, and low cost [31–34]. These attributes enable bulk production and hold tremendous potential in biological fluorescence imaging [35–37]. Besides, CDs doped with various non-metals and metallic elements expand their inherent properties [38–40]. Moreover, CDs possess diverse surface functional groups like –COOH, –NH2, and –OH, enabling further conjugation with various functional molecules [41–43]. Consequently, metal ions with imaging capabilities have been introduced into CDs to impart multimodal imaging functions. Gadolinium (Gd) ions with unpaired 4f electrons are commonly incorporated into contrast agents to generate efficient MR imaging contrast agents. Gd3+doping can sharply reduce the toxicity of free Gd3+ in the body and increase T1
                      relaxivity [44–46]. To give the CT imaging capability of CDs, heavy metal elements like lutetium (Lu) [47–49], ytterbium (Yb), hafnium (Hf) [50–52], tantalum (Ta) [53–55], tungsten (W) [56–58], gold (Au) [59,60], and bismuth (Bi) [61–65] with high atomic numbers, were introduced to nanoparticle-based CAs owing to their excellent X-ray attenuation capacity and higher sensitivity than iodine-based contrast agent. Recently, various Yb-based CAs, e.g., Yb-DTPA [66], Yb2O3 
                     [67–69], NaYbF4 
                     [70–72], were developed due to Yb's lower cost and higher biocompatibility. Furthermore, Yb exhibited higher intrinsic contrast under clinical 120 kV voltage owing to its good match of K-edge (61.3 keV) and the higher energy region at 120 kV [68,73,74]. The metal doping ratios in these CDs are limited (
                        Table S1
                     ) and achieved a relatively lower longitudinal relaxation rate (r1
                     ) and X-ray attenuation capability. CDs for bioimaging are not sufficiently comprehensive, particularly concerning prolonged imaging of deep-seated organs, for further clinical diagnosis (
                        Table S2
                     ) [75–78]. Additionally, more comprehensive toxicity studies are needed especially long-term metal retention toxicity (
                        Table S3
                     ). Therefore, it is urgent to comprehensively develop high-performance and biocompatible metal-doped CDs for in vivo multimodal imaging.

In addition, we measured the dispersity and stability of Yb/Gd-CDs (20 mg mL−1) in various mediums (water, PBS, normal saline, FBS, and RPMI-1640 culture medium). No aggregation was observed in 30 days, indicating prominent colloidal stability of Yb/Gd-CDs (
                           Figure S3
                        ). To assess the chemical stability of Yb/Gd-CDs, the Yb/Gd-CDs was dialyzed for 3 days and the outer solution was collected and incubated with XO indicator. The results indicated that no Yb3+ and Gd3+ leakage was observed, suggesting a good chemical stability of Yb/Gd-CDs (
                           Figure S4
                        ). The above results prove a successful synthesis of Yb/Gd-CDs with good stability, which is beneficial for further use.

The 4T1 tumor CT imaging was carried out on 4T1 tumor-bearing mice. After intravenously injection of Yb/Gd-CDs, the CT value of the 4T1 tumor increased with a visual brightening. The CT value reached 37 HU to a summit of 53 HU at 1 h (
                           Figure S9
                        ). The Yb/Gd-CDs were intratumorally injected into the tumor sites for in situ imaging. The initial CT value of the tumor region was 38 HU, while the CT value dramatically increased to a high value of 560 HU after injection (
                           Figure S10
                        ). Besides, the uniform distribution of the brightening effect observed in the tumor site indicated a good distribution of Yb/Gd-CDs in the tumor site. The above results showed a good CT imaging ability of Yb/Gd-CDs both in vitro and in vivo.
